e Smyrna catastrophe of 1693 and the South Sea Bubble, and makes comparisons with developments in other marine insurance markets. In revealing how the London insurance market changed over centuries, the book discusses issues of risk and uncertainty, the financial revolution, the development of trade, and the reciprocal developmental roles of markets and the state. Overall, it highlights the ways that efficient and effective marine insurance capable of adapting according to circumstance was vital to the growth of trade and the economy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFinancial crisesxHistory. 0aInsurance companiesxHistoryzEnglandzLondon. 0aMarine insurancexHistoryzEnglandzLondon. 4aEarly Modern History. 4aMaritime History. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh  aBritish Maritime History.  aEarly Modern State.  aEconomic History.  aLloyd's of London.  aLondon Marine Insurance.  aMarine Insurance Market.  aMaritime Trade.  aRisk.  aShipping Industry.  aTrade.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311143099740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781800105225?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781800105225423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781800105225/original  a978-3-11-143099-7  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles